body: Which CUDA version do you use?
@fs-eire I am using CUDA 10.2 from within `nvcr.io/nvidia/pytorch:20.03-py3` dev container

the 3rd parameter of function `cudaStreamWaitEvent()` is optional in [latest CUDA API](https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/archive/11.8.0/cuda-runtime-api/group__CUDART__STREAM.html#group__CUDART__STREAM_1g7840e3984799941a61839de40413d1d9) but it's required in [v10.2](https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/archive/10.2/cuda-runtime-api/group__CUDART__STREAM.html#group__CUDART__STREAM_1g7840e3984799941a61839de40413d1d9). 

@junwang-wish Could you help me to quickly check if it works to update line 27 in file onnxruntime\core\providers\cuda\cuda_stream_handle.cc

```cpp
    CUDA_CALL_THROW(cudaStreamWaitEvent(static_cast<cudaStream_t>(device_stream.GetHandle()),
                                        event_));
```

to

```cpp
    CUDA_CALL_THROW(cudaStreamWaitEvent(static_cast<cudaStream_t>(device_stream.GetHandle()),
                                        event_,
                                        0));
```
Yep I changed it like you asked, waiting for the build, it normally takes > 30 minutes @fs-eire

Thanks @pranavsharma and @fs-eire i will close this issue then

> "nvcc fatal   : A single input file is required for a non-link phase when an outputfile is specified" 

When you see this, please go the the build folder and run "make VERBOSE=1", and find the failed nvcc command. Usually, it is because the command has  an extra parameter that nvcc wrongly thinks the extra parameter is a file name.   That's why it says "A single input file is required ". So, without seeing what the full command line, we can't know what went wrong. And, as @pranavsharma said above, we don't support CUDA 10.2 anymore. So very likely the error was because we were using a new parameter that the old CUDA version didn't recognize.
